# Reelattice marketing sync

Before **committing or pushing** app changes (`src/`, `src-tauri/`), compare the **top changelog entry** in `src/lib/changelog.ts` with public-facing copy so first-time visitors and GitHub readers do not miss major features.

Run this in the same session as `reelattice-git-push.mdc` and `reelattice-release.mdc`.

## Surfaces to audit

| Surface | What it advertises |
|---------|-------------------|
| `README.md` | Highlights, Quick start, positioning table |
| `website/src/lib/release-highlights.ts` | Download “What’s new” bullets |
| `website/src/lib/release-highlights.ts` → `MARKETED_CAPABILITIES` | Feature cards / workflow copy source of truth |
| `website/src/components/hero-section.tsx` | Hero promise + live badge |
| `website/src/components/features-section.tsx` | Capability cards |
| `website/src/components/workflow-section.tsx` | Step-by-step workflow |
| `website/src/components/download-section.tsx` | CTA + highlights block |

In-app Help/Changelog are **not** a substitute — many users see README or the website first.

## Classify each changelog bullet

**Marketing-visible** (must appear somewhere public if new or materially changed):

- New tab, workflow, export mode, import behavior, Cases, Settings area
- Platform support, privacy/download/legal behavior
- Headline UX (USB prompt, grid export quality, in-app updates)

**Usually skip for marketing** (changelog + release notes only):

- Visual polish, dialog style swaps, selection highlight fixes
- Performance, tests, single-instance, keyboard tweaks
- Copy-only or internal refactors

When unsure, treat as marketing-visible.

## Gap check (do this every release)

1. Read the newest `CHANGELOG` entry (all bullets).
2. For each **marketing-visible** bullet, confirm it is reflected in **at least one** of: README Highlights/Quick start, `RELEASE_HIGHLIGHTS`, `MARKETED_CAPABILITIES`, hero, features, or workflow.
3. Scan README + website for **stale claims** (removed features, wrong steps, old version promises).
4. If a gap exists → update README and/or website **in the same commit** as the app release. Do not tag until public copy matches.

## What to update when

| Gap type | Update |
|----------|--------|
| New user workflow | README Highlights + Quick start; website features + workflow |
| New export/import option | README Highlights; `MARKETED_CAPABILITIES.export` or `.import`; release highlights |
| New settings behavior visitors care about | README or website features if it is a selling point |
| Patch / polish only | Changelog only; version bump on website if releasing |

## Release highlights rule

`website/src/lib/release-highlights.ts` bullets should summarize the **marketing-visible** items from the top changelog entry — not every bullet. README Highlights can stay broader (evergreen) while release highlights stay version-specific.

## Done when

- [ ] Every marketing-visible changelog item is represented publicly, or consciously deferred with a note in the commit message
- [ ] README and website contain no contradictions with current app behavior
- [ ] `APP_VERSION` and `release-highlights.ts` match the shipped tag (see `reelattice-release.mdc`)
- [ ] Release tag `vX.Y` is pushed — marketing copy without a tag does not ship an app update
